The Crystal Palace flier, Zaha, hopes to make an impact in a competition that boasts Europe-based stars like Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang of Gabon, Algeria's Riyad Mahrez and Sadio Mane of Senegal.Zaha, 24, is a timely addition for The Elephants as many former stars like the Tour brothers - Kolo and Yaya - have retired and star winger Gervinho is injured.The Abidjan-born star has been lured to the African champions by the possibilities of Afcon and 2018 World Cup glory after two friendly appearances for adopted country England.Five reasons why we should give a damn about the 2017 Africa Cup of NationsHe set up the crucial goal in a 2-1 warm-up win over Sweden last Sunday and scored in a 3-0 thumping of fellow Afcon qualifiers Uganda three days later. Ahead of the training camp in the United Arab Emirates, France-born coach Michel Dussuyer admitted that he was concerned about a scarcity of goals.Ivory Coast are in a challenging Group C and kick off their campaign tomorrow against Emmanuel Adebayor-captained Togo, followed by showdowns with the Democratic Republic of Congo and Morocco."The objective is, of course, to defend the title that was proudly acquired in 2015," said Dussuyer, one of 12 European or South American coaches in the 16-team tournament. "It will not be easy."There are fine teams who aspire to win the trophy, but we have the weapons to go far."Morocco are coached by Herv Renard, who guided the Ivorians two years ago to their second Afcon title."I have made reaching the quarterfinals an objective that we absolutely must attain," said Renard, 48. "If we get there, then we will see what we can do."The Frenchman also coached Zambia to glory the last time Afcon was staged in Gabon - jointly with Equatorial Guinea - in 2012.Lightning-quick striker Aubameyang carries the hopes of Gabon, who are expected to make the quarterfinals from a Group A that includes four-time champions Cameroon, Burkina Faso and Guinea-Bissau.As the Borussia Dortmund striker prepares to carry the hopes of the small central African nation on his shoulders, fleet-footed Mahrez will aim to top a great 12 months by taking Algeria to the February 5 final and their first continental title since 1990. Mahrez heads for Gabon fresh from winning the African Player of the Year prize."The next thing after this award is the Africa Cup of Nations. My team will try to do good things there," the France-born star of Leicester City's sensational Premier League title triumph said after securing the Caf prize.</img>Crystal Palace s Wilfried Zaha is a new addition to the Ivory Coast squad. Image: Getty Images Crystal Palace s Wilfried Zaha is a new addition to the Ivory Coast squad. Image: Getty ImagesAlgeria and a Senegal side - the top-ranked in Africa - led by Liverpool forward Mane are the major contenders to succeed the Ivory Coast, who beat Ghana on penalties in the final in Equatorial Guinea two years ago.But they will face each other in a Group B that also contains Tunisia and outsiders Zimbabwe."Our group is difficult, with some top African sides," Mahrez said. "It is not going to be easy with the conditions in Africa, but we have to be prepared."Egypt are back for the first time since winning a record seventh Afcon in Angola in 2010 and will pin their hopes on AS Roma wing player Mohamed Salah.The Pharaohs are one of six teams who qualified, having missed out in 2015. Another, Uganda, will come up against Egypt in Group D, as will Mali and Ghana.Gabon, an oil-rich nation of about 1.8million people, has been in disarray since incumbent President Ali Bongo was declared the winner of a contested election in August. Defeated opposition chief Jean Ping continues to dispute the result and post-election violence has left at least three people dead and saw more than 800 arrested.Opposition activists have called on citizens to boycott Afcon, which will see matches staged in Port-Gentil, Franceville and Oyem as well as the capital, Libreville.Gabon, which in 2014 was awarded the hosting of the tournament due to the turmoil in Libya, is battling with an economic crisis as well as a political one. However, Bongo, who invited Barcelona star Lionel Messi to the country to lay the foundation stone of the stadium in Port-Gentil two years ago, is hoping the football can act as a distraction.He has called for Afcon to be a time for "joy, coming together and shared happiness" and said that "political dialogue will open the day after the tournament".